'''hands down'''

 
Pronunciation: 'han(d)z-'daun
Function: adverb
1 : without much effort : easily
2 : without question 
- hands-down  /'han(d)z-"daun/ adjective 
•[http://www.m-w.com/dictionary/hands%20down Merriam Webster Online Dictionary]

Hands down is a commonly used idiom that describes a situation in which there is either little to no contest, or irrefutable fact.  The origin of this colloquialism seem to have it's roots in mid-19th century horseracing. "A jockey nearing the finish line well ahead of the competition, with victory certain, would often relax his posture and drop his hands, relaxing his hold on the reins, as his steed galloped the final few yards. To win a race 'hands down,' therefore, was to win it easily, without any serious competition, and by the late 19th century the phrase was being used in non-racing contexts to mean 'with no trouble at all.'"•The Word Detective, (Issue of January 15,2002)[www.http://www.word-detective.com/011502.html]